Introduction

My project is an AI drawing game, which will encompass several different game modes in order to produce an experience which is not only as fun as possible, but also re-playable.

In the first, primary, game mode the user will be given an object to draw and a fixed amount of time to draw it. If the AI can guess what this drawing is of before the time has elapsed, then the user is rewarded with points. If the AI cannot guess what this drawing is of, then the user will be awarded no points. This will go on for several rounds the game will then finish, and the user will be told the total number of points which they scored across all the rounds. This first game mode is therefore a high-score oriented game with the objective being to score as many points as possible in a fixed number of rounds. In my game, this game mode is referred to as the Single Player game mode.

In the second game mode, the user will be competing against an AI. The user (and AI) will be given a fixed amount of time to draw a given object. After this time has elapsed, the AI from the first game mode will be used to judge which image is better. In other words, it will output the probability of each image being the specified output. If the users image has the higher probability, the user wins. If the AIs image has the higher probability, the AI will win. As the AI used to classify and judge images is completely separate to the AI used to generate images, there is no risk of bias here. In other words, the game should be fair to the user. In my game, this game mode is referred to as Versus and functions much the same as the Single Player game mode in terms of the user being able to draw objects, and the layout of the program.

Creating the project:

Below are the following tools and components I have decided to use to create my project:

1)      The IDE

The IDE I have decided to use for this project is Microsoft Visual Studio 2019 for the following reasons:

         Visual Studio is a widely recognised development platform meaning frequent updates and bug fixes. This also makes finding help troubleshooting easier, as it increases the likelihood that other people, who are having the same issue with their code, are using the same, or very similar, development environments to what I am.

         Visual Studio supports C#, which is the programming language of choice for this project. However, the majority of AI libraries are only built for Python, due to its simple syntax. Therefore, whilst no Python code is needed when my program is eventually run, I do need to make use of Python to train my two AIs. For this, I will be using Google Colab, which is a version of Jupyter Notebooks by Google which offers better integration with Google Drive, and the offers free GPUs for the purpose of training machine learning models.

         Visual Studio has integration with unity which will make developing the GUI for my program significantly easier. I can make use of templates within visual studio rather than having to start from scratch. For example, when creating a script using visual studio from Unity, it will automatically create the Start() and Update() functions as well as the Class itself.

         It also features a myriad of debugging features, such as the ability to add breakpoints and step through the program a line at a time, in order to identify the part of the code which isnt working properly, variable watch to see the contents of each variable at each step of the program, as well as general colour-coding of functions/variables and intellisense to make small corrections in syntax when writing code, which speeds up the process. It also offers the ability to see real time RAM and CPU usage which, considering my program makes use of machine learning models that are generally resource-intensive, this will be useful when debugging.

         Visual studio also has a built in package library called Nuget, through which all of the libraries I will need for my project can be installed.

 

2)      The Programming Languages

The language I have decided to use for this project is C#.

         C# is a multi-paradigm language which has excellent integration with Visual Studio, which is my IDE of choice.

         C# is object-oriented, which allows my code to be more readable, as well as reusable.

         C# is a simple language, with a garbage collector to manage the allocation and release of memory. Compared to a lower-level language like C or C++, this makes programming in C# significantly easier.

         C# has many built-in or easily importable data structures, such as arrays, lists, and strings, which will make the programming for my project simpler.

         C# is a widely used language, which will make troubleshooting my code easier. Generally, the more popular the language, the more documentation there is, and the better that documentation.

         C# is an extremely efficient and therefore fast language, compared to a language like Python.

Why I chose C# over Python:

Whilst Python has better support for machine learning libraries such as TensorFlow

and Numpy, versions of these libraries do exist for C#, allowing me to make use of

some of the features which C# has that Python doesnt. For example, C# is

significantly better than Python at creating GUIs and at creating programs using

Object-Oriented principles. Creating a GUI in C# with Unity will perform much better

in Windows than using Python and a library such as Tkinter. C# is also much faster

than Python, allowing for better performance of my program overall. In short, C#

ability to create a UI and its better implementation of OOP makes it the

preferred language, in this scenario. However, I will nonetheless need to make use of

Python for training the machine learning model for the Versus game mode, due to

the lack of machine learning libraries for C#. Once trained, this Python code is no

longer needed, and the weights file produced can be accepted by the rest of my C#

code without any issues.

 

3)      Necessary Libraries

My project will require the creation and training of two different and sophisticated neural networks. The first is used to classify the images to determine whether the players drawing is sufficient for them to score points. For this I will use a convolutional neural network (CNN). The second is used to generate images which look like they could have been drawn by a human. This therefore allows the player to compete against the AI i.e. who can draw the best image. For this I will be using a Generative Adversarial Network (GAN). Whilst a normal neural network could be used for both tasks, the accuracy would not be nearly as high. Both of these networks are very complicated and especially complicated to train as the algorithm used to train them (called Back propagation) requires a relatively deep knowledge of multi-variate calculus. It is therefore imperative that I use libraries for this task, and the libraries which I will be using are TensorFlow.NET (a version of TensorFlow, a machine learning library, for C#), Keras.NET (a version of Keras, a high-level machine learning library, for C#), Numpy.NET (a version of the Numpy array library, for C#), as well as the 2D Unity framework for the creation of the UI. Finally, as my program makes use of a persistent store of data in the form of a .json file, I will need to make use of the Newtonsoft.Json library to be able to access and write to this .Json file.

4)      Training Data

The problem in this project is one of supervised learning. In other words, the AI requires data in order to learn from its mistakes. In contrast, in an unsupervised learning problem, the AI would learn from experience; you wouldnt have to feed it data directly you would instead create an environment in which the AI can learn from its mistakes (reinforcement learning).

Therefore, in order for my project to be possible, the dataset already needs to exist as I do not have the resources to gather a sufficient amount of training data myself as, in order for the two AIs to function as intended, training data in the form of millions of images are needed, especially if I want the user to be able to be told to draw a large number of objects.

As a result I will be using the Google Quick Draw dataset (https://quickdraw.withgoogle.com/data) for my project. This dataset features a total of 345 objects, each of which has around 100,000 to 150,000 images associated with it, for a total of roughly 35 million images. I do not have the resources to train my two AIs on all of these images, however I will make use of a small subset of the data to allow for a compromise between number of objects the user can be tasked with drawing, the training time, and the complexity of the machine learning models.

 

5)      Neural Network Architectures

As stated previously, my project will require use of the CNN (Convolutional Neural Network) architecture, as well as the GAN (generative adversarial network) neural network architecture. These will be explained further later on.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Analysis

Recap of the Problem

As stated previously, my project is an AI drawing game which will make use of numerous machine learning algorithms in order to have two distinct game modes. In the first, the user will draw a picture based on a prompt and they score points if the AI can correctly guess what that picture is. In the second, the user will be competing against the AI to see who can draw the best picture in a given time frame.

 

Why the Program is Needed

My program is needed because it not only has an entertainment value in so far as it will be a fun game to play for a wide audience, helping to fill any time where the user cant be productive, but my program may also help users who specialise in art and either wish to increase the pace at which they draw, or to improve their drawings generally. In that sense, my program has a tangible benefit for a specific, if niche, group. Furthermore, my program will fill a gap in the market, as most PC games are either multiplayer, or graphics intensive. My game allows people who dont have time for a full multiplayer game, or dont have a PC powerful enough for most single-player games, to still have fun in their free time. Therefore, there is no doubt that my program is necessary to a specific, if not larger, group of people. Furthermore, the prevalence of time killer games, which my game could be classed under, means there is no doubt that my game will be useful to a select number of users.

 

Stakeholders

Like most applications, my program will have both a target audience which will likely use it frequently, and a more general audience which will use it from time to time. My target audience comprises two distinct groups: artists, and casual gamers. In terms of artists, my program can be used to improve their artistic ability in a fun, yet meaningful way. As my game is also not computationally demanding and does not require a great time or energy commitment to play a single round, the second, larger audience for my program is that of the casual gamer. In other words, people who enjoy gaming as a pastime rather than a hobby.

On average, theres no reason why either of these two groups are going to be particularly well-versed with computers, and so it is important that my game is easy to setup and play. As my project is a windows program, it should be easily attainable to these groups who most likely use the windows operating system and so no conflict of interest exists between my desired target audience and the technology which they will have access to.

Knowledge and Calculations Needed to Understand the Problem and the Code

The Convolutional Neural Network:

As I will not be implementing the neural networks from scratch, the exact calculations needed for this are not necessary. However, in order to understand the code, a basic knowledge of how the network functions is necessary.

In a CNN therefore, the goal is to go from an image to an output which tells us what that image is.

Convolutions:

In simple terms, a convolution is where we multiply a typically 3 * 3 grid of initially random values with our image to obtain a single value, as shown below. This is typically repeated several times, as shown above. The values in this grid of pixels (known as a filter) are then optimised to make sure the network produces the correct output. A standard neural network would flatten the image to be able to access its value. For this reason, convolutional neural networks are advantageous, as each convolution takes into account a grid of pixel values, and their 2 dimensional relation to each other, rather than just taking into account their relation in a single dimension.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 


Max Pooling:

A pooling operation is similar to that of a convolution, except it is used to reduce the size of the image and simplify it.

As shown above, we go over the image with a filter and take the maximum value obtained in that filter and put it into the new image. In this case the filter is 2 * 2. The stride of 2 means that the filter will move to places to the right and 2 places down after each pooling operation, allowing us to half the width and height of the image. This doesnt necessarily help with improving the accuracy of the network, but rather reduces training time.

Fully Connected Layer

After convolving on our image, we flatten it to end up with a standard neural network which will then have a number of nodes equal to the number of classes (where each class is an object which the user will attempt to draw). If the network lights up one node, it means the network is classifying the image as the image which that node represents.

In the image above, the fully connected layer is the section shown below. In this case, there are 10 images which we are trying to classify.

 

The Generative Adversarial Network:

 

 

The above image can be used to explain a GAN. Essentially, we task a neural network, known as the generator, to generate fake images and use a different neural network (known as the discriminator), which would be similar to the CNN described above, to classify them. The idea is that they learn together: the better the discriminator gets at classifying images, the better the generator will get at generating them. Eventually, we can use the fake images created by the generator to draw images in real time whenever we feed it noise. The player will then attempt to draw better images than that of those generated.

Why This Problem is Suited for Being Solved by a Computer and How I Will Use Computational Thinking

My program is suitable for being solved by a computer simply because it allows for a better implementation than one without a computer. Whilst you could draw of your own accord using physical pens and paper, the lack of structure and any kind of objective would make the user get bored much more quickly, and boredom is the problem my program is hoping to solve. Furthermore, writing a program for this allows for a points system, as well as the second game mode where you can compete against an AI

In terms of computational thinking:

I have used decomposition to break this problem down into two game modes and break these two game modes down into the two neural networks, the CNN, and the GAN. Furthermore, the problem is further broken down by being able to implement the same code for the canvas and drawing program for both game modes. As a result, this part of the program can be developed independently from the other two. I can further decompose the UI into its components. For example, I can work on each button of the UI independently of each other and that of the canvas. Furthermore, the program can be easily decomposed in unity through the ability to have different scenes. For example, I have a different scene for the main menu, the Single Player game mode, and the Verus game mode, each of which can be worked on individually. This is even further broken down by there being a number of scripts attached to, or associated with each scene, which I can work on individually. This further helps with debugging, as each script is smaller which not only means that I make fewer mistakes when writing it, but also allows for me to more easily come back to it and debug later on.

I will use abstraction heavily during development. Abstraction is not only an integral part of the training data i.e. all of the training data is grey-scale and inherently lacks detail due to the imposed time limit when they were drawn, but I will also use it when programming the neural networks. As they are too complicated to program from scratch, I will use a high-level library such as Keras to simplify this greatly. In other words, each major step of the neural network can be abstracted into just a single line of code. I will further make use of abstraction in the layout of my GUI. For example, the canvas (the area where you are supposed to draw) can simply be represented by a white box, and the ink of the pen is just a number of simple lines, all with a flat texture, without any of the detail which actual ink would have.

I will also make use of algorithmic thinking heavily during the development of this solution. Both the CNN and the GAN can be considered algorithms, each of which will be run through in a process called Forward propagation whenever we want to either generate or classify an image. Furthermore, there will be a separate algorithm associated with each button, to load the next Unity scene for example. Another example would be in the countdown timer an algorithm (if a simple one) makes it possible to count down from 10 seconds, and to load the next scene after that time has elapsed.

Design

Why I have used decomposition for my solution

The rationale behind systematically breaking my problem down into a series of smaller problems each of which is suitable for computational solutions, can be explained as follows. Decomposition separates the different components of my program from each other, meaning if there is a syntax or logic error in one section of my code, it doesnt have a knock-on effect to the rest of my program. Furthermore, it allows me to test each module individually, ultimately putting them together to get a finished product. This modularity is further advantageous in that it allows me to reuse certain chunks of code, saving time as well as improving its readability. It also makes this problem easier to solve, as it is significantly less daunting to work on a smaller aspect of my program at a time, which also makes finding help with errors much easier. Obviously, someone else with the same problem isnt going to be having it in the exact same environment as me. The specific decomposition of my program is explained below.

 

How I have specifically decomposed my solution

My program can be broken down into a number of separate modules, as shown below:

The CNN:

The CNN is used to classify images drawn by the object. It takes an image as an object and converts it into the item it believes that image is of, from a select list of items. In other words, it is capable of telling the user what it thinks they have drawn. In the form of a diagram, the CNN looks as follows:

The CNN is decomposed into a number of separate functions, each of which performs a slightly different task such as defining, training, and predicting using the CNN. As each function can be tested individually, this is an effective use of decomposition.

Whilst the CNN being its own separate module which is capable of functioning entirely on its own is a good example of how Ive used decomposition for the program as a whole, it is also worth noting that Ive made good use of decomposition as the CNN is composed of a number of different layers. It consists of a convolution layer, a max pooling layer, and an activation layer, each of which is represented by a single line in the pseudocode below.

Defining the CNN Pseudocode

In this pseudocode, we first define the model as Sequential, referring to the fact that the data will move through the neural network in a single direction. Following this, we define 512 3 * 3 filters, allowing for 4608 total trainable parameters in this line of code alone. Each trainable parameter is a value which can be modified through a process called back propagation to allow the neural network to learn, or to map the inputs to the outputs and find the pattern between them. The relu activation function is then applied, allowing for all negative values to become positive, which means it applies the modulus function, essentially making the network more malleable and better able to fit to a dataset. The Max Pooling function then reduces the number of parameters, reducing training time. This is repeated, twice more to increase the number of trainable parameters. Finally, in the last line we flatten the image and connect it to 30 output nodes, where each output node represents a possible object which that image could contain.

Training the CNN Pseudocode

The following procedure can then be used to train the CNN. Here, model is a variable which we defined using the function above. X represents the images which have been converted into a series of arrays which the model can implement, and Y represents the one hot vector associated with each image, which the CNN can interpret as how often it chooses the correct answer. It can then use an algorithm called Backpropagation to improve itself, which is represented by the model.fit line.

In other words, we run the code necessary to map the input to the output. As there are a large number of training examples, the neural network should be able to generalise nicely. This means that when we input an image, the CNN will produce an output similar to that of the dataset in other words, it will have learnt from the dataset.

Predicting using the CNN

After we have trained the CNN, we need to be able to take an image, resize it and convert it into an array, and pass it into the model to get a prediction. Following this, we need to be able to find the index in the one hot vector it returns which is greatest and pass this into a list of ordered items (where the order of items corresponds to the order of the nodes which represent each item) to get a final prediction word for what the CNN thinks that object is, as shown in the pseudocode below.

This prediction word can then be later displayed to the user to inform them on whether they made the correct prediction or not.

Therefore, I have decomposed the CNN into a number of different functions, each of which performs a specific task and can be tested individually.

The GAN

The GAN is the part of my program which generates, or draws images, allowing the user to compete against it in drawing images. The better the images drawn by the GAN or the user, the more points they will ultimately score.

Similarly, to the CNN, the GAN can be decomposed into defining the model, training the model, and then predicting using the trained model. As a GAN essentially includes a CNN as part of its model, the pseudocode for this will be a bit more complicated, and so we decompose the problem further by defining the two component parts of a GAN, the generator and the discriminator, separately.

The Discriminator

The function of the discriminator is extremely similar to that of the CNN itself it takes a sample of images, where roughly half are fake images generated by the generator and the other half are real images from the training set and attempts to classify, and improve its ability over time to classify, which is which. The pseudocode for this looks as follows. As you can see, it looks very similar to that of the CNN. The key difference is the use of the sigmoid activation function, which allows for a single output node and therefore a binary decision 1 means the image is fake, and 0 would mean it is real. We also dont compile the model at this stage like we did with the CNN we need to train them together to ensure that the two models which make up the GAN improve together and based off of each other.

Another distinction is the type of loss we defined. Previously we used categorical_crossentropy, whereas, now that we only have two classes, we instead use binary_crossentropy to better optimiser this neural network for the task at hand. The loss is simply a measure of how mucht the neural network gets wrong.

The cross entropy loss is defined as:

Where y is the y is the actual value for a node in the output layer of the neural network, and ŷ is the predicted value for that node. We then sum over the total number of nodes, which is equal to m, and, for the output layer, will be equal to 30. This sum is out loss, which the neural network will attempt to reduce in an algorithm like back propagation to improve the ability of the neural network to map the input to the output.

The Generator

The generator is designed to take noise and convert it into a fake image which should be indecipherable from the real images in the training set, once the GAN has been trained. The pseudocode for this looks as follows. We apply several convolutions on the image to get a final output image of 28 * 28, identical of that to those in the training set provided by Google.

Here, we have instead used LeakyRelu, an improvement of the Relu function which prevents the neural network from dying, which is referred to as the vanishing gradient problem in machine learning literature.

 

 

 

 

 

The GAN

The GAN itself is just the discriminator and the generator combined in such a manner that they can train off of each other, and improve together to ultimately get a generator which can generate images very similar to those we provided in the training set.

In effect, this allows the GAN to generate an image almost instantly. Its worth noting that, due to the nature of GANs, a single GAN can only generate one class of images. Therefore, if we want to tell the GAN to produce an image of a specific object, we need to train the GAN 30 separate times for each of the 30 objects in our training set, in order to produce 30 .h5 files which we dynamically load in when necessary in the drawing game itself.

Google Quick Draw

Main Menu

Furthermore, the main menu describes what the game is about. For a browser-based game, this makes the most sense. However, as my game needs to be downloaded, the user would already know what the game is about if they have it downloaded, so I do not think this is necessary for my game.

Development Phase 1

The development of my coded solution can be split into 3 separate agile phases, each of which mostly be tested and developed independently of each other. The rationale behind this is to allow for the feedback of the specific stakeholder to affect the outcome of the solution as much as possible. The more often the feedback from the specific stakeholder, the greater their feedback will affect the final design of the coded solution, and so the better my program will match their needs. Furthermore, it allows me to effectively decompose the problem each phase will have different goals and can be considered independently of the other stages, hence easing development.

The goals for this first phase of development are to:

         Set up the object classes for my program, including the use of OOP techniques such as encapsulation, and later inheritance and polymorphism.

         Create a basic GUI for my program, which can be improved in phase 2.

         Ensure that my program has basic functionality through being both able to draw an object and through implementing the necessary buttons needed for this to happen.

         Give the stakeholder an outline of how my coded solution will look and operate and use their feedback to influence my development in phase 2.

Using a Singleton To Transfer Data Between Scripts and Scenes

In Unity, in order to attach a script to a game object, it needs to inherit from a class called Monobehviour, which makes accessing data from classes more difficult and makes it harder to keep track of instantiated objects. As we need to constantly keep track of important data, such as which round we are on, which item needs to be drawn, how many points the user has, etc, we need to have a way of storing this data. One method is to use a file, such as a .json file. This wouldnt be a very good implementation as it constantly means that data which isnt persistent (for example, there is no need to keep track of which round the user is on after the game has finished) needs to be written to disk. As the speed of disks can vary greatly and we need to ensure that the path of that file is the same on any computer, it makes much more sense to store this data in RAM which is a much quicker data. To do this, we use a Singleton, a form of Unity object designed for retaining data between Unity scenes. The data which is persistent, such as the high scores of the user, will need to have a persistent store of data. However, this development will take place in the second phase. The code for the singleton is defined below, and you can see that it contains all of the attributes which we need to retain between scenes.

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 


A Singleton works through making use of the Awake() function in Unity, which is called before any other code in the program. I therefore will attach the Singleton to the main menu, to initialise all of the necessary attributes the instant the game is run.

The singleton will trigger the DontDestroyOnLoad() function, to ensure that the singleton is kept when the next scene is loaded, as shown below.

The above will be shown in the inspector irrespective of what scene is currently open. Therefore, the attributes will be accessible regardless of what scene is currently open.

Another advantage of a Singleton is that it allows me to see the attributes whilst the code is running, which is extremely useful for debugging purposes. I can see all of the values while the game is running to check that they are updating correctly and correspond to what is currently being shown in the Unity scene.

         I created a PredictOnImage() function as a placeholder for the 3rd phase of development where I will work on the creation of the convolutional neural network.

         I iterated the number of rounds by one using the Singleton, allowing for me to later check how many rounds have taken place and to end the game.

         The AI will return a number, imax, which corresponds to the neuron in the fully connected layer (I.e. the output layer) of the convolutional neural network which has the maximum value. This maximum value will be between 0 and 1 as the softmax activation function is applied at this layer. In other words, it is the neuron with the highest probability, and as there are 30 neurons at this layer, it represents the object which the CNN has predicted the drawing is of. As the CNN was trained on one hot vectors, where a 1 in the first index represents the first item in the alphabetical list, we can return the item in the list of items with this index of imax. This is predictionword, which is what the CNN predicts the drawing is of.

         We then simply need to check if this value is the same as what the drawing is supposed to be of. If it is, we give the user a point and load a Postroundwon scene. If it isnt, we load a Postroundlost scene.

The Postroundwon scene simply congratulates the user with scoring a point and allows them to move onto the next round of the game.

Training an AI to recognise images

As mentioned previously in the analysis stage, the game works by prompting the users to draw a specific image. If the AI can successfully guess what the user had drawn, the user is awarded with a point. If it cannot, then the user will be rewarded with no points for that round. Therefore, I need to train an AI to be able to recognise all of the images which we may task the player with drawing. In order to maximise the replay value of this game, there should be at least 30 different classes (30 different possible objects which we task the player with drawing).

In order to do this, the data needed to train the AI needs to be gathered.

Gathering the Training Data for the AI

The data which I am using for this project is the same used for Quick, Draw! by Google, which is on Github. This was a necessity to gather a sufficient amount of training data myself, and to have a reasonable number of classes (i.e. objects) would be almost impossible. This dataset comprises almost ten million images which I simply would not be able to gather myself.

As this data was stored on Google Cloud, I had to first download the Google Cloud SDK shell and download the data in the .npy form:

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 


However, this data was in the form of .npy files, which I cannot use to train my neural network. Therefore, I had to write a Python script to convert these files into .JPEG, which I can then use during training. This also prevented errors from arising later on. With a single .npy file, there could be ambiguity about where one image ends and the next one begins, whereas when all of the images are separate, this is much clearer. Furthermore, it allows me to make use of an ImageDataGenerator to train the AI using images from disk. Alternatively, if they were all stored in an array, they would be stored in RAM and there are too many images in the dataset for that to be possible.

The python script converts each image in the dataset into a corresponding .JPEG image.

This code therefore creates folders for all 345 objects within the dataset and fills these folders with the .JPEG images.

It works by reading the names of each of the .npy files and creating folders with those names with the .npy removed. After this, I could convert each of the .npy files to a number of .JPEG images, which my AI will accept.

In other words, instead of each of my images being contained within a single .npy file, which would make it difficult to know when one image starts and the next begins, each of my images are instead stored separately as .JPEGs within a single folder, as follows:

 

 

 

 

 

 


I then selected 30 images of the 345 classes out of the dataset. I selected these 30 according to their difficulty in drawing, and how common that object is. This therefore allowed me to have a range of objects of different difficulties and different abundances, whilst reducing training time and the re-playability of my game (as, if there were too few objects, the game would soon get boring). In other words, this is an example of me having to delimit my game in order to reduce training time and how computationally expensive my solution is.

Training the AI itself

The AI in question is a form of neural network called a convolutional neural network (CNN). Whilst the majority of machine learning libraries only exist for Python, there is one library, called Keras.NET, which would allow me to create a convolutional neural network relatively simply. Fortunately, this package is popular enough that I could simply install it using NuGet, which is built into Visual Studio.

I could then write the following code to train and compile a convolutional neural network, with the exact details of the network being similar to that of a CNN which performs well on the MNIST dataset (a dataset consisting of numbers from 0 to 9 with the same size dimensions for the images as in my dataset).

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

After initially defining the model in the first line, the next 3 sets of 3 lines are the same. Each create 32 new filters, each of them being 3 * 3 in size such that they have 9 weights which we then adjust during training. The Relu activation function is then added, which improves the ability of the network adapt to different functions and therefore increases its efficacy, and finally we add a MaxPooling layer to reduce the sizes of the images which in turn reduces training time. In other words, it extracts the key features of the images and leaves the rest behind.

Finally, we flatten the features extracted by the network and feed them into a standard neural network. This then allows us to add dropout which discourages the neural network from simply memorising the images within the dataset and instead encourages it to learn the features which make up that image (through randomly killing off specific neurons to prevent the neural network from becoming overly reliant on them, hence preventing overfitting). We can then have 30 neurons on the output, as we have 30 different classes, and the softmax activation function allows for the output of the network to be turned into a probability. In other words, the sum of the values at each neuron in the output layer will sum to 1, as intended.

In summary, this network will produce a probability of the image you input into it being a particular object.

 

Training the CNN

The following code can then be utilised to train the neural network. We do this by giving the network images in batches which reduces training time as otherwise we would be adjusting the weights of the network after every image. The epochs hyperparameter then specifies how many times we pass the neural network the full dataset. Through experimenting, I found the ideal number to be around eleven (meaning the network will have seen each image eleven times by the time it finishes training). Ten epochs is generally a rule of thumb when training neural networks, and so finding the ideal number to be eleven validated that my network was likely to be functional.

The result of this training therefore ultimately produced a convolutional neural network trained to recognise drawings of 30 different objects, with a training set accuracy of over 90%.

Training the GAN for the Versus game mode

The second AI of which I am making use of in my program is a form of neural network called a generative adversarial network. Due to the lack of documentation for Keras.NET, I had to use Python to train the GAN itself. The code for this section therefore looks very similar to that of the previously designed pseudocode. However, the training of the GAN only needs to be done once. Once trained, the GAN will similarly produce a .h5 file which can be loaded and be used for forward propagation within C# and Unity. The Generator:

         It has a similar architecture to that of a CNN, but without the fully connected layer (the output layer used for classification).

         It is used to try and generate fake images. This part of the network is the only part used after training to generate, or draw, an image.

The Discriminator:

         The discriminator is essentially a convolutional neural network, and so has an almost identical architecture to the CNN used in the Single Player game mode.

         It is used to try and decipher between the real images in the training set, and the fake images generated by the generator. This part of the network is only used during training.

We then can define the GAN, which is a combination of the two models allowing them to both work, and improve, together when training.

Inputting into the GAN Model

A GAN works by the generator taking in noise as an input, and the discriminator taking in the real images.

In order for the discriminator to be given real images, we first need to convert each image into the correct format. In other words, each image needs to consist of a 2 dimensional array with values from -1 to 1 (instead of 0 to 255):

Evaluation and Beta Testing

Functional and Robustness Testing

The specific stakeholder for my project helped me in ensuring that my program was rigorously tested to ensure that it is as functional as possible.

The two main types of testing are functional and robustness testing when it comes to testing a piece of software. Functional testing refers to verifying that each function, or feature, of the software works properly and operates in accordance with the specification (the success criteria, in this case). On the other hand, non-functional testing refers to testing the non-functional aspects such as usability, performance, reliability. To put it simply, functional testing ensures that the code is doing the right things, whereas non-functional testing verifies that the code is doing these things in the right way (i.e. with the correct implementation).

Comparison of the Final Product against the Success Criteria.

For the quantitative success criteria:

         In the success criteria, I stated that the game should have measurable criteria, such as the CNN having an accuracy of 90% or above. I partially met this success criteria. Whilst my CNN did have a training set accuracy of 93% after eleven epochs, the training set accuracy is not usually trusted in machine learning. This is because it is possible for the CNN to overfit or essentially memorise the images in the training dataset, rather than looking for the pattern between them. This means that the training accuracy could be 100% even if the real-world performance of the neural network is sub-par, as it has essentially cheated and remembered the images in the dataset. A suitable analogy would be a human memorising a mark scheme rather than properly studying for a test. To remedy this, a validation set, and even in addition a test set, can be used and the accuracy on this test set are usually seen as valid and representative of the real world. However, as this requires taking data out of the training set, I instead decided to have fewer metrics about the efficacy of my network in order to give it additional data, and therefore improve its ability to recognise objects (even if it means being unable to state a numerical score which represents the performance of my AI).

         In the success criteria, I stated that, in a sample of forty images, where half are from the dataset, and the other half generated by the GAN, I should not be able to tell the difference between them. I also partially met this success criteria. The images generated by my GAN have inverted colours and so, without first inverting the colours, I would be able to distinguish the two images. However, I did do this test through first inverting the colours of the images generated by the GAN, and the GAN was able to pass this success criteria. Although, as inverting the images was a pre-requisite, I would argue that I only partially met this point of the success criteria.

Limitations of the Final Product

My final product also had several limitations. However, these were mostly expected from the outset.

Limitation 1: The game only has 30 objects.

         Whilst there are 345 total objects in the training set, which total over 10 million images, my final game only has 30 objects. The reasons for this are twofold: The first is that, using that many images would make the training process extremely unstable and likely to crash. Secondly, training neural networks on over ten million images would take an extremely long time, especially considering that the GAN needs to be trained separately on each object it is able to draw. Thirdly, the fewer the number of objects, the greater the efficacy of the AI. This makes logical sense even a human, who is good at recognising objects, would have a greater chance of getting it right if they only had 30 objects to choose from, rather than 345.

Limitation 2: The GAN produces low resolution images.

         This is a limitation of the training dataset. The images in the training dataset are only 28 * 28. Any neural network is only as good as the data it is trained on, and so the images drawn by the GAN are fairly blocky and low resolution. Unfortunately, there is nothing I could really do about this, as the Google Quick Draw dataset is the best dataset for images of drawings by humans. However, I could perhaps improve this in future development through applying some sort of upscaling algorithm/AI, or maybe some sort of anti-aliasing, although this would have a great deal of complexity, and therefore would require a lot of development time.

Limitation 3: The program is only available on Windows.

         Ideally, my game would have been available on every platform. However, I wanted to include .EXE files to improve the stability of my game when performing the forward propagation of my neural networks. This meant that my game became Windows-only. In future development, this could maybe be improved through having some sort of implementation involving injecting the necessary .dll files instead, although I am not entirely sure how that would work.

How the System Will be Maintained in the Future

From the functional and usability testing, my stakeholders and I were able to undoubtedly prove that my code is incredibly robust and is able to correctly respond to a variety of different circumstances and inputs by the end user. This not only makes my code more readable, but also improves the stability of my program, as it is much more difficult for the user, either maliciously or by accident, to cause my program to break or otherwise not function as intended.

In terms of code maintenance, the use of comments throughout my code will allow for me in the future, or for other developers, to fully understand the code which I have written and, in addition, makes my code much easier to trace. Furthermore, I have proven that my code is very robust, not just through the testing in this evaluative stage, but also through the use of validation at a variety of points in my program. Furthermore, all of my code is set out in classes, which inherently makes it all procedural, but it has also allowed me to make use of OOP techniques which further improve the robustness, and readability, of my code, as well as reducing its length. For example, I have made use of encapsulation, inheritance, and polymorphism in my program. Finally, the use of running processes (i.e. running the necessary .EXE files) also prevents my game from crashing and means that, in the worst-case scenario, the game will display an error, rather than causing Unity to crash, further evidencing the robustness of the program which I have been able to create.

TimerField.cs

using System;

using System.Collections;

using System.Collections.Generic;

using System.Text.RegularExpressions;

using UnityEngine;

using UnityEngine.UI;

using TMPro;

 

public class TimeField : MonoBehaviour

{

public string amountoftime;

public GameObject inputField;

public GameObject textDisplay;

private string regexpattern;

public TextMeshProUGUI warningtext;

 

public TimeField()

{

this.regexpattern = @"^(1[01][0-9]|120|[5-9]|[1-9][0-9])$"; //Check if between 5 and 120

}

 

public void Store()

{

amountoftime = inputField.GetComponent<Text>().text;

UnityEngine.Debug.Log(amountoftime);

//Use REGEX to check that it is in the correct range:

Singletonattributes.Instance.amountoftime = Int32.Parse(amountoftime);

 

try

{

 

if (Regex.IsMatch(amountoftime, regexpattern)) //Check if it's in the range of 5 to 120.

{

Singletonattributes.Instance.amountoftime = Int32.Parse(amountoftime);

 

}

else

{

warningtext.text = "Invalid input!";

Singletonattributes.Instance.amountoftime = 10;

}

 

 

}

 

catch (Exception error)

{

UnityEngine.Debug.Log(error.Message);

}

 

 

}

 

}

PointsOOP.cs

using System;

using System.IO;

using System.Collections;

using System.Collections.Generic;

using System.Text.RegularExpressions;

using UnityEngine;

 

public class PointsOOP// : MonoBehaviour

{

private string topscore;

private int roundpoints;

private string regexpattern = "@^(10|[0-9])$";

 

public PointsOOP()

{

this.roundpoints = Singletonattributes.Instance.pointcounter;

}

 

public void WriteTopScore()

{

try

{

string json = File.ReadAllText("E:/CS Project/imageprediction/topscsores.json");

dynamic jsonObj = Newtonsoft.Json.JsonConvert.DeserializeObject(json);

topscore = jsonObj["topscore"];

 

if(Regex.IsMatch(topscore, regexpattern)) //Check if it's in the range of 0 to 10.

{

if (roundpoints > int.Parse(topscore)) //Check that it is in the correct range:

{

jsonObj["topscore"] = roundpoints;

}

}

 

 

}

 

catch (Exception error)

{

UnityEngine.Debug.Log(error.Message);

}

 

}

 

}

Draw_behaviour.cs

using System.Collections;

using System.Collections.Generic;

using UnityEngine;

 

public class Draw_behaviour : MonoBehaviour

{

public Camera m_camera;

public GameObject brush;

private float thickness;

 

public LineRenderer currentLineRenderer;

 

Vector2 lastPos;

 

private void Update()

{

 

thickness = Singletonattributes.Instance.thickness;

Drawing();

}

 

void Drawing()

{

if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Mouse0))

{

CreateBrush();

}

else if (Input.GetKey(KeyCode.Mouse0))

{

PointToMousePos();

}

else

{

currentLineRenderer = null;

}

}

 

void CreateBrush()

{

GameObject brushInstance = Instantiate(brush);

currentLineRenderer = brushInstance.GetComponent<LineRenderer>();

//currentLineRenderer.startColor = Color.green;

//currentLineRenderer.endColor = Color.green;

currentLineRenderer.material.SetColor("_Color", Color.blue);

currentLineRenderer.material.SetColor("_EmissionColor", Color.blue);

//because you gotta have 2 points to start a line renderer,

Vector2 mousePos = m_camera.ScreenToWorldPoint(Input.mousePosition);

 

 

currentLineRenderer.SetWidth(thickness, thickness);

currentLineRenderer.SetPosition(0, mousePos);

currentLineRenderer.SetPosition(1, mousePos);

 

}

 

void AddAPoint(Vector2 pointPos)

{

currentLineRenderer.positionCount++;

int positionIndex = currentLineRenderer.positionCount - 1;

currentLineRenderer.SetPosition(positionIndex, pointPos);

}

 

void PointToMousePos()

{

Vector2 mousePos = m_camera.ScreenToWorldPoint(Input.mousePosition);

if (lastPos != mousePos)

{

AddAPoint(mousePos);

lastPos = mousePos;

}

}

 

public void Delete()

{

Destroy(brush);

}

 

}

CountDownTimerOOP.cs

using System.Collections;

using System.Collections.Generic;

using UnityEngine;

using TMPro;

using UnityEngine.UI;

using UnityEngine.SceneManagement;

using System.IO;

using System.Linq;

using System.Drawing;

using System.Threading;

using System.Windows;

using System.Threading.Tasks;

 

namespace Timer

{

public class CountDownTimerOOP// : MonoBehaviour

{

protected float currentTime;

protected string prediction;

protected TextMeshProUGUI countdowntext;

protected TakeaScreenshot takescreenshot;

protected CNN_OOP predictusingcnn;

 

public CountDownTimerOOP(TextMeshProUGUI countdowntext)

{

this.currentTime = Singletonattributes.Instance.amountoftime;

this.countdowntext = countdowntext;

this.takescreenshot = new TakeaScreenshot();

this.predictusingcnn = new CNN_OOP();

 

 

}

 

//Getters and setters needed for currenTime and startingTime

 

public float CurrentTime

{

get

{

return currentTime;

}

 

set

{

currentTime = value;

}

 

}

 

public TextMeshProUGUI CountdownText

{

get

{

return countdowntext;

}

 

set

{

countdowntext = value;

}

}

 

 

public virtual void CountDown() //Virtual keyword allows us to override this method.

{

 

currentTime -= 1 * Time.deltaTime;

countdowntext.text = currentTime.ToString("0");

 

if (currentTime <= 0)

{

currentTime = 10;

 

takescreenshot.Screenshot();

int imax = predictusingcnn.StartProcessContingency();

ColorPicker.cs

using System;

using System.Collections;

using System.Collections.Generic;

using UnityEngine;

using UnityEngine.UI;

using UnityEngine.Events;

using TMPro;

 

[Serializable]

public class ColorEvent : UnityEvent<Color> { }

public class ColorPicker : MonoBehaviour

{

public ColorEvent OnColorPreview;

public ColorEvent OnColorselect;

public TextMeshProUGUI DebugText;

RectTransform Rect;

Texture2D ColorTexture;

 

// Start is called before the first frame update

void Start()

{

Rect = GetComponent<RectTransform>();

ColorTexture = GetComponent<Image>().mainTexture as Texture2D;

}

 

// Update is called once per frame

void Update()

{

if(RectTransformUtility.RectangleContainsScreenPoint(Rect, Input.mousePosition))

{

Vector2 delta;

RectTransformUtility.ScreenPointToLocalPointInRectangle(Rect, Input.mousePosition, null, out delta);

string debug = "mousePosition=" + Input.mousePosition;

debug += "<br>delta=" + delta;

 

float width = Rect.rect.width;

float height = Rect.rect.height;

 

delta += new Vector2(width * .5f, height * .5f);

debug += "<br>offsetdelta" + delta;

 

float x = Mathf.Clamp(delta.x / width, 0f, 1f);

float y = Mathf.Clamp(delta.y / height, 0f, 1f);

 

debug += "<br>x=" + x + " y=" + y;

 

int texX = Mathf.RoundToInt(x * ColorTexture.width);

int texY = Mathf.RoundToInt(y * ColorTexture.height);

debug += "<br>texX=" + texX + " texY=" + texY;

 

Color color = ColorTexture.GetPixel(texX, texY);

 

DebugText.color = color;

 

DebugText.text = debug;

 

OnColorPreview?.Invoke(color); //Check if preview is null

 

if (Input.GetMouseButtonDown(0)) //Left click

{

OnColorselect?.Invoke(color);

}

}

}

}

EXEForCNNPredict.cs

using System;

using System.Collections.Generic;

using System.Linq;

using System.Text;

using System.Threading.Tasks;

using System.IO;

using System.Windows;

using Keras;

using Keras.Callbacks;

using Keras.Layers;

using Keras.Models;

using Keras.Optimizers;

using Keras.PreProcessing.Image;

using Keras.Initializer;

using Keras.Utils;

using Numpy;

using Keras.Regularizers;

 

namespace EXEForCNNPredictv5

{

class Program

{

static int Main(string[] args)

{

List<string> items = new List<string>();

 

//predict

var cnn = Model.LoadModel("E:/CS Project/imageprediction/trainedafteroneepoch30classesmoreparameters.h5");

int img_width = 28;

int img_height = 28;

var img = Keras.PreProcessing.Image.ImageUtil.LoadImg("E:/CS Project/imageprediction/croppedprediction.png", target_size: (img_width, img_height));

var img_smaller = Keras.PreProcessing.Image.ImageUtil.ImageToArray(img);

var img_correct_format = Numpy.np.expand_dims(img_smaller, axis: 0);

var predictions = cnn.Predict(img_correct_format);

//Console.WriteLine(prediction);

//var reader = new StreamReader("E:/CS Project/pythoncodetest/items.txt");

 

 

//for some reason the predictions contains integers - will have to come back to this!

 

//Console.WriteLine(predictions);

var predictionsasarray = predictions.GetData<float>();

//Console.WriteLine(predictionsasarray[0]);

//create list of items

foreach (string item in File.ReadLines("E:/CS Project/imageprediction/finalitemlist.txt"))

{

items.Add(item);

}

//find index of highest value

int imax = 0;

for (int i = 0; i < items.Count; i++)

{

if (predictionsasarray[i] > predictionsasarray[imax])

imax = i;

}

//Console.WriteLine("imax is" + imax.ToString());

 

//imax is the index of predictionsasarray with the greatest value (confidence)

//Therefore:

float confidence = predictionsasarray[imax];

Console.WriteLine("confidence is" + confidence.ToString());

 

//Console.WriteLine(confidence);

string json = File.ReadAllText(@"E:/CS Project/imageprediction/properties_new.json");

dynamic jsonObj = Newtonsoft.Json.JsonConvert.DeserializeObject(json);

//Console.WriteLine(confidence);

jsonObj["confidence"] = confidence;

string output = Newtonsoft.Json.JsonConvert.SerializeObject(jsonObj, Newtonsoft.Json.Formatting.Indented);

File.WriteAllText(@"E:/CS Project/imageprediction/properties_new.json", output);

 

//Console.ReadKey();

//File.WriteAllText(@"E:/CS Project/imageprediction/properties.json", String.Empty);

 

/*

using (StreamWriter w = File.AppendText(@"E:/CS Project/imageprediction/properties.json"))

{

//w.WriteLine("output is " + output);

//w.WriteLine("confidence is " + confidence);

w.WriteLine(output);

 

}

*/

 

return imax;

}

}

}
